DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Thank you,
[? Marin. ?] [? Marin ?] told

00:00:54.330 --> 00:00:57.880
me that she was a really
great Google stalker.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:01.260
And wonderful bio, thank you.

00:01:01.260 --> 00:01:03.250
What's that?

00:01:03.250 --> 00:01:04.170
I'm looking off.

00:01:04.170 --> 00:01:05.640
Where are you?

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:08.740
How many folks in this
room like to drink?

00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:09.910
Cocktails, yeah?

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:11.710
Show of two hands,
perhaps, that.

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:15.170
How many of you in this room
think that you, perhaps,

00:01:15.170 --> 00:01:19.569
have a good pallet or at
least an inquisitive one?

00:01:19.569 --> 00:01:20.360
You like to go out.

00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:21.000
You like to learn.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:22.208
You like to taste new things.

00:01:22.208 --> 00:01:23.500
OK.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:25.580
I'm that guy, as well.

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:27.132
I found at a very
early age-- and I

00:01:27.132 --> 00:01:30.520
was sharing with [? Marin ?]
earlier-- that two decades ago,

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:33.750
during my first summer abroad,
which was when I was 18,

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:36.740
I spent it between high
school and summer in Europe.

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:38.160
You can drink legally there.

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.860
And I learned a lot
about myself that summer.

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:43.100
And one of the
things that I learned

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:46.560
is that I was most concerned
about flavor and texture

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:48.860
and not just the buzz
that I was getting

00:01:48.860 --> 00:01:50.400
from that pint of Guinness.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:53.050
And it led me down
a path, or shall

00:01:53.050 --> 00:01:57.420
we say a rabbit hole, which
I'm in these two decades later.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:00.870
This book that's right here,
"Drinking the Devil's Acre,"

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:02.270
is many things.

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:06.540
In addition to narrative,
memoir, and history,

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:09.880
it's also part
cultural anthropology.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:12.730
And one of the things that
I was most interested in

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:15.320
is studying this
community, thinking

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:18.370
about San Francisco as the
epicenter of the Bay Area,

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:20.140
of the culture of
Northern California,

00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:21.940
and how the culture
of California

00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:24.590
has historically been
connected to cocktails.

00:02:24.590 --> 00:02:27.490
And what I learned was that
it was also historically

00:02:27.490 --> 00:02:31.080
connected to how we taste, OK?

00:02:31.080 --> 00:02:33.730
In this book, I
make an assertion

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:35.740
that we actually
learn to taste first.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:39.350
And our palates became developed
first via the cocktail,

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:40.760
all right?

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:42.810
So again, I'm Duggan McDonnell.

00:02:42.810 --> 00:02:46.870
And a few months ago, this book,
"Drinking the Devil's Acre,"

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:48.820
was published.

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:49.690
It's history.

00:02:49.690 --> 00:02:51.250
It's memoir.

00:02:51.250 --> 00:02:54.790
And it tells all of these
years of my time shaking,

00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:59.070
and then drinking, behind
the stick, as well.

00:02:59.070 --> 00:03:01.050
What I'm most passionate
about, as I said,

00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:04.320
is how San Franciscans drank
and came to understand flavor.

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:06.700
And what I'd love to
hear from you today

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:09.390
is whether you agree with
me and whether you've also

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:11.890
experienced this.

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:17.370
The title of this talk is
Bright, Bitter, and Boozy.

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:21.040
Perhaps some of you in this
room can relate to at least one

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:23.040
of those three adjectives.

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:25.870
Whether you're native to the
Bay Area or a recent emigre who

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:29.060
happens to chug
many a cocktail, I

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:31.650
believe that's what we all are.

00:03:31.650 --> 00:03:33.160
So here in Northern
California, I'm

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:36.980
here to tell you that your
culture-- our culture--

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:40.510
first experienced
flavor via cocktails.

00:03:40.510 --> 00:03:45.540
Our palates found enlightenment
by sipping, not chewing.

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:48.880
Again, the culture
of the Bay Area

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:51.990
first acquired its understanding
and its passion for flavor

00:03:51.990 --> 00:03:57.830
through the cocktail glass,
not via fork and plate.

00:03:57.830 --> 00:04:01.350
I'm going to read just a
few lines from this book

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:03.290
so that you understand.

00:04:03.290 --> 00:04:06.510
"San Francisco began
as a city of drink.

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:10.260
And from its infancy, discerning
and decisive San Franciscans

00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:12.990
tippled by calling out
the name of their drink.

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:16.360
The city did not begin with
that ribald Barbary Coast,

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:19.959
nor was it the Arizona or the
Colorado of the Wild West,

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:24.340
where thirsty pioneers
dumbly hollered 'whisky.'

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:25.390
No, no, no.

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:28.540
This was the San Francisco of
the Gold Rush, the Comstock

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:33.512
Lode, a city shaped by the 'Big
Four' and other robber barons.

00:04:33.512 --> 00:04:37.540
The prevailing culture spoke
civilly to, rather than shouted

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:42.580
at, the barkeep, 'whisky smash,
if you please, cherry cobbler,

00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:46.110
if you don't mind,
claret and lemonade,

00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:49.590
if it's no trouble.' It
wasn't a culture that barked

00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:50.590
for straight hooch.

00:04:50.590 --> 00:04:52.980
Instead, the tune
sung throughout

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:57.900
was of freshly squeezed
citrus, sprigs of peppermint,

00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:03.510
dashes of bitters
here and there."

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:07.520
So come along with me and think.

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:12.450
Cocktails offer an
explosion of flavor.

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:14.750
They're liquid combinations
of wine and spirit,

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:19.660
liqueur, fresh produce,
dashes of bitters, tinctures.

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:23.760
And most of these
ingredients are shelf stable.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:26.680
They can travel across the
world in the hull of a ship,

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:29.200
ready to be blended by
the ounce behind the bar

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:33.420
when they are finally chosen
by their destined barkeep.

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:37.515
Let's remember this old
cocktail called the Martinez.

00:05:37.515 --> 00:05:41.830
An Abrahamic cocktail, the
forerunner to the martini,

00:05:41.830 --> 00:05:46.360
it tastes of clove, juniper,
cinnamon, orange peel,

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:53.910
tart cherry, vanilla, sassafras,
bitter orange, cardamom.

00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:57.170
Rare is that rare
steak that could offer

00:05:57.170 --> 00:05:59.200
such an abundance of flavor.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:01.910
But this cocktail can.

00:06:01.910 --> 00:06:07.480
San Francisco, because it has
been bright, bitter, and boozy

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:11.130
from its first week as a city
known round the world in 1849,

00:06:11.130 --> 00:06:15.910
has had at the core of its
identity this burst of flavor.

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:18.350
The fastest-growing,
richest city

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:21.360
in the history of the
world got to drink

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:24.220
what it wanted to drink.

00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:27.180
And then, San
Francisco got spoiled.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:29.040
We got used to good drink.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:32.000
Does that sound familiar, folks?

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.730
The richest city in the
history of the world?

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:37.070
What is this Bay Area now?

00:06:37.070 --> 00:06:39.797
We have a few bucks
going around, don't we?

00:06:39.797 --> 00:06:41.380
And isn't there a
cocktail Renaissance

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:44.130
that's been happening,
as well, simultaneously?

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:46.730
It's an interesting
phenomenon, isn't it?

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:50.490
150ish years ago, San
Francisco had a lot of options,

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:54.670
principally, a large
menu from which to drink.

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:57.510
Then, as now, the
city was a port city.

00:06:57.510 --> 00:07:01.110
And it was the port that
fed the city in ideas,

00:07:01.110 --> 00:07:04.110
in human populations,
and in drink.

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:07.690
Into this port came the
largest, most diverse stream

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:12.780
of champagne, port, Jamaican
rum, Scotch whisky, Dutch gin,

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:16.470
Bourdeaux, Pisco from
Peru, just to name a few.

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:21.010
Never before had such a
collection of wine and spirits

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:23.920
ever been on offer.

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:28.240
Never before had a city sprung
up, seemingly overnight,

00:07:28.240 --> 00:07:31.680
from mountains of
harvested gold.

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:34.730
And again, it was because
of all that gold--

00:07:34.730 --> 00:07:39.040
that great disposable income--
that San Francisco commanded

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:41.631
the world's finest drink.

00:07:41.631 --> 00:07:43.380
Does that sound like
some of the back bars

00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:45.540
that you go and see
in the city today,

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:49.240
where there's 400 bottles
lining the shelves,

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:50.875
and the bar keep
gets to play with all

00:07:50.875 --> 00:07:52.830
of these different flavors?

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:57.536
That was happening in the 1850s.

00:07:57.536 --> 00:08:00.580
And so imagine
that old bar keep.

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:01.530
Let's think, huh?

00:08:01.530 --> 00:08:05.360
Mustache, oil cloth, OK?

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:06.200
You're just here.

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:07.730
Perhaps it's your first job.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:10.320
And you're standing in front
of all of the splendor.

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:13.203
And you think, what am I going
to do with all this stuff?

00:08:13.203 --> 00:08:13.970
Huh?

00:08:13.970 --> 00:08:16.220
What would you do?

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:17.760
You'd start mixing,
wouldn't you?

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:19.770
I think I'd feel at home.

00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:23.340
And I would've started mixing,
just as I have done recently.

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:26.310
You see, from its birth,
again, San Francisco

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:28.756
has been a city of innovation.

00:08:28.756 --> 00:08:30.380
And "Drinking the
Devil's Acre" reveals

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:32.289
that much of that
early innovation

00:08:32.289 --> 00:08:35.580
actually happened in the saloon.

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:38.280
The great spirits of the world
captivated the imagination

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:40.419
of the first generation
of mixologists.

00:08:40.419 --> 00:08:43.549
And to work they went.

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:46.120
And for that, I'm
quite thankful.

00:08:46.120 --> 00:08:51.330
By the time 1881 arrived and
California's first cookbook

00:08:51.330 --> 00:08:55.290
was finally published, no less
than the world's first four

00:08:55.290 --> 00:08:59.780
cocktail books had come from
the city's finest bar keeps.

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:03.460
Newspapers were full of
advertisements for apothecaries

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:06.160
for homemade bitters.

00:09:06.160 --> 00:09:08.840
And I should share with you,
the first piece of fiction

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:12.040
ever published in
California was called "Punch

00:09:12.040 --> 00:09:14.780
Drinking and Its Effects."

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:17.710
First piece of fiction
published in our state

00:09:17.710 --> 00:09:19.210
was about a cocktail.

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:21.840
The local landscape was
lousy with breweries,

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:23.530
lousy with local distilleries.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:24.700
Then came the wineries.

00:09:24.700 --> 00:09:28.550
And then finally
into full bloom came

00:09:28.550 --> 00:09:32.500
the drinking culture of Northern
California, the most prolific

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:35.320
and the greatest contributor
of intellectual property

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:39.480
to drink the world
will ever know.

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:41.760
This is something
that I'm proud of.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:43.740
This is something,
frankly, that makes

00:09:43.740 --> 00:09:45.095
our lives a lot more delicious.

00:09:48.270 --> 00:09:50.430
Close your eyes with me.

00:09:50.430 --> 00:09:53.850
The Gold Rush, the Comstock
Lode, the whaling years,

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:55.510
railroad barons.

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:59.690
The Martinez, the whisky
smash, the gin fizz, punches,

00:09:59.690 --> 00:10:01.940
sours, and flips.

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:05.550
IBM, Apple, YouTube.

00:10:05.550 --> 00:10:09.570
The Mai Tai, the lemon
drop, Pisco punch.

00:10:09.570 --> 00:10:12.840
Friendster, Facebook.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:17.580
The chartreuse swizzle,
the basil gimlet, Google,

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:24.010
and the Irish coffee-- all
of these, local innovations,

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:26.250
the greatest diversity of
liquid decadence the world

00:10:26.250 --> 00:10:27.560
has ever known.

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:33.570
And together, money and
cocktails shall ever flow.

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:36.450
Now let's return to why San
Francisco learned specifically

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:39.440
about flavor from drink.

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:41.640
Produce is perishable, yes?

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:44.250
Requiring preservation
for travel.

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:49.660
Not so, a barrel of rum
or a bottle of sherry.

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:53.330
Meats and vegetables today
benefit from refrigerated box

00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:56.050
cars, trucks perfectly
chilled, much of it

00:10:56.050 --> 00:10:59.500
frozen, right, while
traveling America's highways.

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:03.090
Now California cuisine could not
and did not develop to anything

00:11:03.090 --> 00:11:07.490
like it is today until long
after electric generators were

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:12.220
developed, mass produced,
until highways were chock full

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:17.080
with trucks traveling from
farm to city every single day.

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:19.930
It's a very recent phenomenon.

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:23.240
Our palates were first
informed by drink.

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:27.280
And in California, it is a
bright, bitter, and boozy

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:30.210
pallet we have.

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:32.560
So what do I mean by bright?

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:33.868
Does it have an IQ?

00:11:33.868 --> 00:11:35.272
[LAUGHS]

00:11:36.210 --> 00:11:39.940
Is it merely something, say,
citric-- a little fresh lemon

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:42.940
in your water or
in your martini?

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:45.760
It can be, as citrus
was first cultivated

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:47.910
in the United States
by the Spanish fathers

00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:50.300
here, in early California.

00:11:50.300 --> 00:11:54.930
But without balance-- a
little sugar-- citric really

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:58.740
just means acidic, which can
be too tart, which can be,

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:01.590
frankly, yuck, all right?

00:12:01.590 --> 00:12:04.210
So I mean that cocktails
in Northern California

00:12:04.210 --> 00:12:07.100
are abundant with citrus,
whether for its juice

00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:10.750
to be squeezed or for
essential oils found

00:12:10.750 --> 00:12:12.640
in the skins of
lemons and oranges

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:18.680
to be expressed over, into
Negronis, Old Fashioneds.

00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:21.600
And I do not mean citrus
come from Florida.

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:22.870
What do I mean?

00:12:22.870 --> 00:12:26.630
Local satsumas,
local Meyer lemons

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:28.530
because that is
what prevails here.

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:31.740
Because when produce is fresh,
the height of its flavor

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:34.385
experience is, in fact, higher.

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:42.030
By bright, I also
mean herbaceous.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:48.440
What was the name of
the little Spanish town

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:51.330
at the end of the
mythic peninsula

00:12:51.330 --> 00:12:53.440
before it became known
as San Francisco?

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:54.900
Does anybody know?

00:12:54.900 --> 00:12:56.190
AUDIENCE: Yerba Buena?

00:12:56.190 --> 00:12:59.310
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Yerba Buena,
says the gentleman in row two.

00:12:59.310 --> 00:12:59.810
Right.

00:12:59.810 --> 00:13:04.190
And that means "good herb," as
it was called by the Spanish,

00:13:04.190 --> 00:13:06.610
for all the plentiful
wild mint that

00:13:06.610 --> 00:13:09.850
was grown all over the land.

00:13:09.850 --> 00:13:12.730
Trader Vic, that
native San Franciscan,

00:13:12.730 --> 00:13:16.250
who created the Mai
Tai, the Scorpion Bowl,

00:13:16.250 --> 00:13:19.990
amongst many other wildly
imaginative offerings--

00:13:19.990 --> 00:13:24.640
his favorite garnish of
choice was a mint sprig--

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:27.980
smacking it-- something bright,
something to sort of heighten

00:13:27.980 --> 00:13:32.210
that aromatic
experience of cocktails.

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:37.630
And in the mid '90s, long
before the mojito craze

00:13:37.630 --> 00:13:40.640
swept the country,
that lovely high ball,

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:43.947
bright with fresh mint,
was alive and well

00:13:43.947 --> 00:13:44.655
in San Francisco.

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:50.420
Let's talk about bitterness.

00:13:50.420 --> 00:13:52.380
Has anyone ever
experienced bitterness?

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:55.220
In a cocktail, hmm?

00:13:55.220 --> 00:13:56.760
Sure, sure, sure.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:59.000
Well, San Francisco
has long been bitter.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.457
But it's actually been
a preference of ours.

00:14:02.457 --> 00:14:04.040
I mentioned that in
the Gold Rush era,

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:08.250
dozens of brands of local
bitters were being produced.

00:14:08.250 --> 00:14:12.810
They were consumed for health--
folk medicine, if you will.

00:14:12.810 --> 00:14:16.390
And the ingredients used
were this amazing combination

00:14:16.390 --> 00:14:21.250
of local produce, along
with exotic roots and spices

00:14:21.250 --> 00:14:26.830
freshly imported from the
Andes or from Canton China.

00:14:26.830 --> 00:14:29.280
And as bitters
became ubiquitous,

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:33.200
so too did these San
Francentric combinations

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:37.360
of bitter global flavor.

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:41.280
Fast forward to World War I, OK?

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:45.700
Northern Italy becomes a
front in a vicious fight.

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:50.360
Trench warfare ensues, and the
entire region is destabilized.

00:14:50.360 --> 00:14:53.540
Within the next decade,
tens of thousands

00:14:53.540 --> 00:14:56.150
of immigrants from
Northern California

00:14:56.150 --> 00:14:59.710
came to San Francisco and
settled in the North Beach

00:14:59.710 --> 00:15:00.550
region.

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:06.890
With them, they brought their
two local preferred hamaros.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:08.820
What are the names
of those brands?

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:13.230
Campari, Fernet-Branca, OK?

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:17.160
If you've ever wondered how San
Francisco acquired its passion

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:22.811
for the Negroni cocktail or
for chugging shots of Fernet,

00:15:22.811 --> 00:15:25.490
not only does it go
back to North Beach

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:27.540
and that northern
Italian migration

00:15:27.540 --> 00:15:29.480
during the '20s,
which was prohibition,

00:15:29.480 --> 00:15:32.440
remember, but also before that.

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:34.420
This region has
preferred something

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:40.720
bitter on the pallet
for nearly 150 years.

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:43.580
Let's talk about
being boozy, shall we?

00:15:43.580 --> 00:15:46.610
Many of you asked if I'd brought
my samples with me today.

00:15:46.610 --> 00:15:48.619
I'm sorry, I did not.

00:15:48.619 --> 00:15:50.410
In the old days, the
port of San Francisco,

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:56.250
and today, the Port of Oakland,
receives more coffee beans

00:15:56.250 --> 00:15:57.880
than any other
port in the world.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:00.410
Does anyone know that?

00:16:00.410 --> 00:16:02.480
Why am I talking about coffee?

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:03.630
Stay tuned.

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:05.340
Long ago, it was
Hills Brothers, which

00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:07.620
was located on the
waterfront, that dominated

00:16:07.620 --> 00:16:10.020
the national coffee landscape.

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:12.980
Today, a few different
companies, but locally, we

00:16:12.980 --> 00:16:17.060
have artisanal brands--
Blue Bottle, Equator.

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:20.420
But now, let's remember the
most widely known coffee

00:16:20.420 --> 00:16:26.220
drink all over the world,
which comes from San Francisco,

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:28.330
has what in it?

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:32.250
A slug of whisky-- the
Irish coffee, folks.

00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:35.862
One of the drinks that San
Francisco is most famed for,

00:16:35.862 --> 00:16:39.530
its most famous coffee drink,
actually has booze in it,

00:16:39.530 --> 00:16:40.720
and quite a bit of it.

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:43.920
Has anyone here been
to the Buena Vista?

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:49.180
Full house, perfect. [LAUGHS]
I'm a local, and I go often.

00:16:49.180 --> 00:16:51.050
Northern California,
with its breweries,

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:55.340
wineries, and distilleries
produces the largest amount

00:16:55.340 --> 00:16:57.590
of alcohol in the country.

00:16:57.590 --> 00:16:59.150
That should come as no surprise.

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:03.900
California as a state
also imports and consumes

00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:05.780
the largest amount of
alcohol in the nation.

00:17:08.450 --> 00:17:10.948
It is boozy to its core.

00:17:10.948 --> 00:17:16.839
And so I wonder, folks, with all
this alcohol, these experiences

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:24.210
of bright, of bitter, and boozy,
I wonder if we think better.

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:27.180
I wonder if we perform better.

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:29.650
I wonder if we
work harder because

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:33.360
of that delicious, abundant
reward of great drink

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:34.820
all around us.

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:36.860
I think that there's
a connection.

00:17:36.860 --> 00:17:41.190
I wonder how intrinsically
linked cocktails just

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:45.390
might be to the world's
great culinary region,

00:17:45.390 --> 00:17:49.240
to the center of innovation.

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:52.660
I'll leave you with a quote
from Doris Muscatine's epic

00:17:52.660 --> 00:17:56.300
book, "Old San Francisco,"
which I quote in my book.

00:17:56.300 --> 00:17:57.540
And it's one of my favorites.

00:17:57.540 --> 00:18:02.240
And I think it describes
San Francisco, then and now,

00:18:02.240 --> 00:18:04.090
perfectly.

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:09.080
She says, "Drinking was
such a fact of city life

00:18:09.080 --> 00:18:11.360
that it was certainly
considered no disgrace

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:14.630
to frequent a saloon, which
the entire populace did

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:16.630
without embarrassment.

00:18:16.630 --> 00:18:19.230
Since everybody acknowledged
that everybody drank,

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:22.665
large-scale social drinking
became taken for granted.

00:18:22.665 --> 00:18:25.880
And there was consequently
little stigma attached.

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:34.930
San Francisco has never lost
its enthusiasm for alcohol."

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:36.114
Thank you for your time.

00:18:36.114 --> 00:18:39.130
And now I'd like to hear from
you what your thoughts are

00:18:39.130 --> 00:18:41.080
on being bright,
bitter, and boozy,

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:42.640
some of your favorite
watering holes,

00:18:42.640 --> 00:18:44.875
cocktails to make or shake.

00:18:47.490 --> 00:18:48.410
Go ahead.

00:18:48.410 --> 00:18:51.192
AUDIENCE: I'm going
to boozy and bitter.

00:18:51.192 --> 00:18:52.150
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Yeah.

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:55.770
AUDIENCE: Isn't it true
that Anchor Brewery sort of

00:18:55.770 --> 00:18:58.551
invented the modern IPA?

00:18:58.551 --> 00:19:01.050
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: I would say
that would be our fine friends

00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:02.050
up in Chico.

00:19:02.050 --> 00:19:03.130
AUDIENCE: In Chico.

00:19:03.130 --> 00:19:04.010
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Sierra Nevada.

00:19:04.010 --> 00:19:04.335
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:19:04.335 --> 00:19:06.626
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: But one of
the things that Anchor did

00:19:06.626 --> 00:19:11.700
was revive the rye
whisky revolution.

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:13.290
I have the year in the book.

00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:16.620
But I think it was,
perhaps, it was '97 or '99.

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:21.050
And Anchor became the first and
only distillery in the United

00:19:21.050 --> 00:19:24.520
States to make 100% rye whisky.

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:27.350
And that wasn't
happening anywhere.

00:19:27.350 --> 00:19:29.250
Well, here we are,
again, San Francisco

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:30.861
long ahead of the curve.

00:19:30.861 --> 00:19:33.360
And we're in the midst of not
only a whisky revolution right

00:19:33.360 --> 00:19:35.550
now but a rye revolution.

00:19:35.550 --> 00:19:38.600
The old fashioned is one of
the most popular cocktails

00:19:38.600 --> 00:19:39.340
in the country.

00:19:39.340 --> 00:19:43.950
Whisky has outpaced
vodka in recent sales.

00:19:43.950 --> 00:19:46.540
And it all goes back, I
think, to the late '90s,

00:19:46.540 --> 00:19:48.850
when Fritz Maytag,
the previous owner,

00:19:48.850 --> 00:19:51.150
said I'm going to do this.

00:19:51.150 --> 00:19:53.990
It's time that America
sort of take back

00:19:53.990 --> 00:19:55.440
it's rye whisky heritage.

00:19:55.440 --> 00:19:57.780
And in fact, long before,
say, there were vines

00:19:57.780 --> 00:19:59.405
planted throughout
Northern California,

00:19:59.405 --> 00:20:00.670
it was actually fields of rye.

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:01.837
So it was a local thing.

00:20:01.837 --> 00:20:03.670
So the distilleries
that were happening here

00:20:03.670 --> 00:20:08.899
in the 1860s and '70s produce a
ton of specifically rye whisky.

00:20:08.899 --> 00:20:09.940
That was his inheritance.

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:10.770
That's our inheritance.

00:20:10.770 --> 00:20:11.770
So I'm glad he did it.

00:20:11.770 --> 00:20:13.853
AUDIENCE: Thank you for
touching on the connection

00:20:13.853 --> 00:20:15.710
between wealth and drinking.

00:20:15.710 --> 00:20:16.760
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Mm-hm.

