but they're working on that.

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:41.120
But there is a
distillery up in Sonoma

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:46.750
by the name of--
folks, what is it?

00:21:46.750 --> 00:21:47.400
Spirit Works?

00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:48.358
AUDIENCE: Spirit Works.

00:21:48.358 --> 00:21:50.540
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Yeah,
they also make the sloe gin.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:54.100
They are just about to
launch a straight rye whisky.

00:21:54.100 --> 00:21:55.270
And I tasted it last week.

00:21:55.270 --> 00:21:56.530
It's very nice.

00:21:56.530 --> 00:21:58.130
AUDIENCE: So are they local?

00:21:58.130 --> 00:21:59.844
Are they actual
local distilleries?

00:21:59.844 --> 00:22:01.510
They are distillering
their own alcohol?

00:22:01.510 --> 00:22:02.968
DUGGAN MCDONNELL:
So yeah, they are

00:22:02.968 --> 00:22:06.745
what you would call part of
the grain-to-glass movement.

00:22:06.745 --> 00:22:08.120
Where the question
is coming from

00:22:08.120 --> 00:22:10.780
is that the great majority
of whisky in this country

00:22:10.780 --> 00:22:14.300
is actually made
by very few people.

00:22:14.300 --> 00:22:17.330
There's a couple distilleries
in the middle of the country

00:22:17.330 --> 00:22:19.881
that everyone just buys
from and then re-distills

00:22:19.881 --> 00:22:20.880
or does their own thing.

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:21.930
Or they say, hey,
this is our recipe.

00:22:21.930 --> 00:22:23.340
You guys make it,
and give it to us.

00:22:23.340 --> 00:22:25.756
And then we'll finish it, or
we'll barrel it or something.

00:22:25.756 --> 00:22:27.860
Some part of that
process is largely

00:22:27.860 --> 00:22:30.280
what's happening in the country.

00:22:30.280 --> 00:22:33.340
There are certain folks, like
Buffalo Trace, Wild Turkey,

00:22:33.340 --> 00:22:35.690
they do everything on their own.

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:38.010
But for instance,
there are brands

00:22:38.010 --> 00:22:39.780
that are largely outsourced.

00:22:39.780 --> 00:22:42.020
The local guys now
are trying to be

00:22:42.020 --> 00:22:44.350
more a part of this
California ethos, which

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:45.807
is the grain-to-glass movement.

00:22:45.807 --> 00:22:47.640
And I think we're going
to see more of that,

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:49.960
not just here but
throughout the country.

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:51.020
AUDIENCE: More of the--

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:53.530
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: More of
the grain-to-glass movement--

00:22:53.530 --> 00:22:56.170
basically, controlling the
ingredients and all the steps

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:59.524
to ensure quality and
also to be able to connect

00:22:59.524 --> 00:23:01.440
with your consumer to
say, look, we made this.

00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:02.064
And here's why.

00:23:02.064 --> 00:23:04.110
And you can answer
every single question

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:06.970
because your steps are
vertically integrated.

00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:10.040
You know exactly how
everything's been made.

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:11.500
AUDIENCE: You also
mentioned some

00:23:11.500 --> 00:23:13.081
herbs coming from the Andes?

00:23:13.081 --> 00:23:14.080
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Mm-hm.

00:23:14.080 --> 00:23:15.390
AUDIENCE: For instance what?

00:23:15.390 --> 00:23:19.140
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Sure, well,
coca leaves used to be legal.

00:23:19.140 --> 00:23:22.430
But quinine, [INAUDIBLE]
cinchona bark,

00:23:22.430 --> 00:23:27.140
is the main one that did and
does still come from Peru.

00:23:27.140 --> 00:23:30.290
Quinine is the principal
ingredient in what?

00:23:30.290 --> 00:23:30.844
Anyone know?

00:23:30.844 --> 00:23:31.510
AUDIENCE: Tonic.

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:34.557
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Tonic, mm-hm.

00:23:34.557 --> 00:23:36.390
So not just in tonic
water, but before that,

00:23:36.390 --> 00:23:39.820
it was in many different
formulas for bitters.

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:43.850
And there's other things coming
from down there, as well.

00:23:43.850 --> 00:23:46.990
So and of course, San Francisco
being on the Pacific, stuff

00:23:46.990 --> 00:23:48.690
would stop off in
those ports down here.

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:49.440
They'd load it on.

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:50.670
They'd do some commerce.

00:23:50.670 --> 00:23:52.527
Come up here to the
Port of San Francisco--

00:23:52.527 --> 00:23:53.610
another layer of commerce.

00:23:53.610 --> 00:23:57.020
And then folks would take
them to their "pharmacies"

00:23:57.020 --> 00:23:59.440
and have at it.

