And are there any flavors
you think that we've

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:44.497
lost that we should rediscover?

00:25:44.497 --> 00:25:46.080
DUGGAN MCDONNELL:
Hmm, great question.

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:46.955
Thank you for asking.

00:25:46.955 --> 00:25:49.170
So I think that here
in California, we

00:25:49.170 --> 00:25:53.510
began with a bright, bitter, and
boozy palate, and we lost it.

00:25:53.510 --> 00:25:56.240
And I think that we're actually
in the process of gaining it

00:25:56.240 --> 00:25:56.740
back.

00:25:56.740 --> 00:26:00.562
I think that the middle
20th century screwed us up.

00:26:00.562 --> 00:26:04.820
On the food side, everything
was available in a can, right?

00:26:04.820 --> 00:26:07.200
Or it was frozen or
something like that.

00:26:07.200 --> 00:26:09.320
And that became true,
not just in food,

00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:11.860
by having cans of beans
and meats and vegetables,

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:13.820
but also with cocktails, right?

00:26:13.820 --> 00:26:16.630
All of a sudden,
everything came in a mix.

00:26:16.630 --> 00:26:19.104
And it was some funny color
so, like, the guys in space

00:26:19.104 --> 00:26:20.520
could just grab a
bunch of bottles

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:22.829
and go have a cocktail party.

00:26:22.829 --> 00:26:24.620
They didn't know there
was a farm anywhere.

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:27.470
And that went on for decades.

00:26:27.470 --> 00:26:30.730
And recently, call it
the whole-foods movement

00:26:30.730 --> 00:26:34.110
or some sort of farmers
market, farm-to-glass movement,

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:38.040
if you will-- we're
starting to get this back.

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:39.780
Anytime you put
anything fresh in there,

00:26:39.780 --> 00:26:41.480
it's going to be brighter.

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:43.050
But it's also going to sway.

00:26:43.050 --> 00:26:46.090
So because that flavor
is alive, right,

00:26:46.090 --> 00:26:47.750
and it's changing in your glass.

00:26:47.750 --> 00:26:51.010
So we're starting to
see cocktails that

00:26:51.010 --> 00:26:52.530
have to be made with precision.

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:54.770
So we're getting better
in our recipes, all right.

00:26:54.770 --> 00:26:57.470
Because we have better
access to ingredients, now

00:26:57.470 --> 00:27:00.400
and also, thankfully
to the internet,

00:27:00.400 --> 00:27:03.340
we have this access
to information

00:27:03.340 --> 00:27:04.630
like we've never had before.

00:27:04.630 --> 00:27:07.470
It used to be you had
to publish a book.

00:27:07.470 --> 00:27:10.750
And people had to buy a
book to get great stories

00:27:10.750 --> 00:27:11.500
and great recipes.

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:12.950
That's not true anymore.

00:27:12.950 --> 00:27:15.180
You can find a lot of
information on the internet.

00:27:15.180 --> 00:27:18.020
And so now, if you
go to your BevMo!

00:27:18.020 --> 00:27:21.490
and your Whole Foods and
you have a smartphone,

00:27:21.490 --> 00:27:22.925
you can make amazing cocktails.

00:27:22.925 --> 00:27:24.300
And that's the
era that we're in.

00:27:24.300 --> 00:27:27.290
And so I think we're
regaining that.

00:27:27.290 --> 00:27:31.940
I think it's so wild that
kale and arugula is popular.

00:27:31.940 --> 00:27:34.350
But then you might think
that it's also wild

00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:37.970
that homemade bitters
and tinctures from bell

00:27:37.970 --> 00:27:40.960
peppers and many other things
are also just as popular.

00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:44.430
And I think all of that is
informing our palate, so

00:27:44.430 --> 00:27:46.127
on the plate and in the glass.

00:27:46.127 --> 00:27:47.460
That's where we're at right now.

00:27:47.460 --> 00:27:50.859
And I think it's only going to
continue because of this access

00:27:50.859 --> 00:27:51.400
that we have.

00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:55.430
And I can't imagine going
back into the dark ages

00:27:55.430 --> 00:27:58.350
of a couple decades ago.

00:27:58.350 --> 00:28:04.170
I grew up thinking that most
green beans came from a can.

00:28:04.170 --> 00:28:06.110
How about you?

00:28:06.110 --> 00:28:08.239
AUDIENCE: I grew up in
California, so not so much.

00:28:08.239 --> 00:28:10.030
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: I
grew up in Santa Clara,

00:28:10.030 --> 00:28:13.030
OK, the next county down.

00:28:13.030 --> 00:28:17.490
And we had a garden, but a
garden yields, what, couple

00:28:17.490 --> 00:28:18.907
of meals worth?

00:28:18.907 --> 00:28:21.240
Most of the green beans had
a Jolly Green Giant on them.

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:22.820
And there was
commercials about him.

00:28:22.820 --> 00:28:25.730
He was my friend.

00:28:25.730 --> 00:28:28.050
And that was my
experience with food.

00:28:28.050 --> 00:28:30.130
And I think we're never
going to go back there.

00:28:30.130 --> 00:28:31.550
I hope, at least.

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:33.530
AUDIENCE: How do
you start creating?

00:28:33.530 --> 00:28:37.170
And what's your approach
to creating a new cocktail?

00:28:37.170 --> 00:28:38.200
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Hmm.

00:28:38.200 --> 00:28:41.060
So how do I create
new cocktails?

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:45.730
Quite honestly, because I've
been thinking about alcohol

00:28:45.730 --> 00:28:48.280
and flavor for
over two decades, I

00:28:48.280 --> 00:28:51.830
have a big bank between
the small space in my ears.

00:28:51.830 --> 00:28:54.340
It's all taken up with
boozy flavors and ideas.

00:28:54.340 --> 00:28:58.430
And so even if I taste something
new for the first time,

00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:01.430
I can then associate it with
hundreds of other things.

00:29:01.430 --> 00:29:05.040
And the ideas
mostly come quickly.

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:06.930
And I don't even
need to make them.

00:29:06.930 --> 00:29:09.580
I know what it's going to taste
like ahead of time because I

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:11.371
do all of the balance
in my head and I know

00:29:11.371 --> 00:29:13.050
the structures and all that.

00:29:13.050 --> 00:29:16.760
I'm constantly doing
development like that.

00:29:16.760 --> 00:29:18.760
And it's sort of like composing.

00:29:18.760 --> 00:29:20.792
I can create the theory
in my head first.

00:29:20.792 --> 00:29:21.750
And then I can make it.

00:29:21.750 --> 00:29:24.995
Yeah, that kind of stacks
up to exactly how I thought.

00:29:24.995 --> 00:29:27.840
And I might adjust it by a
quarter or a half ounce, one

00:29:27.840 --> 00:29:30.730
thing or the other,
and it's done.

00:29:30.730 --> 00:29:33.570
But again, that's only come
from decades of drinking

00:29:33.570 --> 00:29:35.644
and thinking about drink.

00:29:35.644 --> 00:29:37.935
One of the things that I do,
though, when I'm training.

00:29:37.935 --> 00:29:40.350
And one of the things that
I make all of my staff

00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:43.540
do, and it's the second or third
to last chapter in this book,

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:47.446
is I talk about the most
important tool behind any bar.

00:29:47.446 --> 00:29:49.760
Can anyone think
about what that is?

00:29:49.760 --> 00:29:50.770
Is it a shaker?

00:29:50.770 --> 00:29:51.670
Is it a muddler?

00:29:51.670 --> 00:29:53.170
Anyone know?

00:29:53.170 --> 00:29:55.380
It's a straw, OK?

00:29:55.380 --> 00:29:56.355
It's the tasting straw.

00:29:56.355 --> 00:29:57.360
And I grab it like this.

00:29:57.360 --> 00:29:58.151
And I go like this.

00:29:58.151 --> 00:30:00.380
And I pop it in, and I taste.

00:30:00.380 --> 00:30:04.420
And every single time I'm making
a cocktail-- you're my guests,

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:07.200
you're at my bar, you order
a margarita or a manhattan.

00:30:07.200 --> 00:30:09.960
It's the same recipe
I've made 10,000 times.

00:30:09.960 --> 00:30:13.290
But I dip and I taste
just to make sure.

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:14.990
I'm not looking to get drunk.

00:30:14.990 --> 00:30:18.370
That 16th of an ounce is not
going to hurt me in any way.

00:30:18.370 --> 00:30:20.250
But what I'm doing
is always affirming.

00:30:20.250 --> 00:30:22.730
But I'm also-- it's
quality control there.

00:30:22.730 --> 00:30:25.080
I'm making sure that
something isn't off,

00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:27.960
that the vermouth
hasn't gone bad

00:30:27.960 --> 00:30:30.290
or that perhaps the lime
was too sour, too acidic,

00:30:30.290 --> 00:30:31.699
and I need to adjust.

00:30:31.699 --> 00:30:33.240
Or perhaps I didn't
shake it as long,

00:30:33.240 --> 00:30:35.175
so there's not enough dilution.

00:30:35.175 --> 00:30:36.550
Or enough air
didn't get in there

00:30:36.550 --> 00:30:38.910
to open up the flavors--
all of those things.

00:30:38.910 --> 00:30:40.900
So not only have I just
tasted all the bottles

00:30:40.900 --> 00:30:42.480
and tasted a lime
or a pineapple,

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:45.540
but I've tasted these
combinations hundreds

00:30:45.540 --> 00:30:46.830
of thousands of times.

00:30:46.830 --> 00:30:49.230
And so I understand
the relationships.

00:30:49.230 --> 00:30:51.820
And that's what I would
advocate is to always

00:30:51.820 --> 00:30:53.500
be tasting and thinking.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:54.734
Have that cognizance.

00:30:54.734 --> 00:30:56.650
AUDIENCE: I have one
more if nobody-- [LAUGHS]

00:30:56.650 --> 00:30:57.500
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Hit me.

00:30:57.500 --> 00:30:59.250
AUDIENCE: So on the,
again, going back to,

00:30:59.250 --> 00:31:02.980
like, the food movements,
away from sugar in general,

00:31:02.980 --> 00:31:04.490
but particularly
refined sugar, do

00:31:04.490 --> 00:31:06.480
you see a trend going
that same direction?

00:31:06.480 --> 00:31:08.250
Because sugar's a very
essential component

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:09.910
of cocktails and balance.

00:31:09.910 --> 00:31:11.010
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Hmm.

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:12.800
So talking about
sweeteners, I think

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:18.310
that we've almost lost corn
syrup in the bar world.

00:31:18.310 --> 00:31:22.630
There are certainly-- there's
mixers that still use it.

00:31:22.630 --> 00:31:25.440
But those mixers have just
been downgraded so much

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:27.380
that no one's interested.

00:31:27.380 --> 00:31:30.260
We also know how to
make syrups on our own

00:31:30.260 --> 00:31:33.760
now-- it's easy-- with
fruit and sugar and water.

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:34.790
So there's that.

00:31:34.790 --> 00:31:38.930
There's also 100% cane
movement that's going on.

00:31:38.930 --> 00:31:41.780
And then there's many different
types of cane out there

00:31:41.780 --> 00:31:44.240
and processed cane, whether
you're talking about Turbinado

00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:47.680
or finding molasses
or using unbleached.

00:31:47.680 --> 00:31:49.410
There's many different
things out there.

00:31:49.410 --> 00:31:52.390
And then you have alternate
sugar sources, right.

00:31:52.390 --> 00:31:55.430
Within the last
dozen years, we've

00:31:55.430 --> 00:31:57.950
seen an explosion
of agave nectar,

00:31:57.950 --> 00:32:00.920
right, as a sweetener,
which does not give you

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:05.100
much of a glycemic hit, sort
of more of a steady drip

00:32:05.100 --> 00:32:08.380
into your system, which also
provides a nice sweetening

00:32:08.380 --> 00:32:10.450
viscosity in cocktails.

00:32:10.450 --> 00:32:12.890
Specifically, it's
popular now in margaritas,

00:32:12.890 --> 00:32:15.966
almost changing that
classic margarita recipe

00:32:15.966 --> 00:32:17.340
from tequila,
lime, and Cointreau

00:32:17.340 --> 00:32:20.109
to tequila, lime,
and agave nectar.

00:32:20.109 --> 00:32:22.650
And that's pretty much the San
Francisco margarita now-- very

00:32:22.650 --> 00:32:24.530
healthy and a lighter style.

00:32:24.530 --> 00:32:26.250
And then, of course,
we've got honey.

00:32:26.250 --> 00:32:30.240
Folks are-- cocktail bars
now across the country

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:31.660
are lousy with honey.

00:32:31.660 --> 00:32:33.370
And I think that's
a great thing.

00:32:33.370 --> 00:32:36.410
You make a honey syrup, and
then you employ that in.

00:32:36.410 --> 00:32:38.669
And again, different
sweeteners are coming about.

00:32:38.669 --> 00:32:39.960
Does that answer your question?

00:32:39.960 --> 00:32:41.940
I think that's both
healthier, and it's also

00:32:41.940 --> 00:32:44.950
expanding flavor
possibilities, both of which

00:32:44.950 --> 00:32:47.160
I think are important.

00:32:47.160 --> 00:32:48.881
AUDIENCE: So I guess
about a year ago I,

00:32:48.881 --> 00:32:50.880
for the first time, moved
into an apartment that

00:32:50.880 --> 00:32:53.290
actually has room for a bar.

00:32:53.290 --> 00:32:54.060
So I've--

00:32:54.060 --> 00:32:54.820
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Good for you.

00:32:54.820 --> 00:32:55.540
AUDIENCE: --been developing a--

00:32:55.540 --> 00:32:56.220
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: You've
got your priorities right.

00:32:56.220 --> 00:32:57.260
AUDIENCE: I got my
priorities right, yeah.

00:32:57.260 --> 00:32:59.590
So for the first time,
now I have sort of a bar.

00:32:59.590 --> 00:33:02.080
And I've got 20 to 30
bottles or something.

00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:04.160
But I'm wondering,
how do you look

00:33:04.160 --> 00:33:05.670
about developing a home bar?

00:33:05.670 --> 00:33:08.240
What are the things that
you look for to expand it

00:33:08.240 --> 00:33:09.970
or the tools that you want or--

00:33:09.970 --> 00:33:10.830
DUGGAN MCDONNELL:
Great question--

00:33:10.830 --> 00:33:11.788
expanding the home bar.

00:33:11.788 --> 00:33:14.230
What an important thing, right?

00:33:14.230 --> 00:33:15.230
There's books out there.

00:33:15.230 --> 00:33:16.200
I think there's one
that just came out

00:33:16.200 --> 00:33:17.910
called "The 12 Bottle Bar."

00:33:17.910 --> 00:33:19.530
So perhaps buy that one.

00:33:19.530 --> 00:33:21.389
There's a lot of blogs
out there on that.

00:33:21.389 --> 00:33:22.930
But essentially, I
think you probably

00:33:22.930 --> 00:33:26.860
need to have one of each of
the major spirit categories

00:33:26.860 --> 00:33:28.450
out there.

00:33:28.450 --> 00:33:33.950
But finding that bottle can
be a difficult thing, OK.

00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:35.930
And, say, when you're
judging your vodka,

00:33:35.930 --> 00:33:39.340
don't judge it by cracking
it, pouring it neat,

00:33:39.340 --> 00:33:41.549
lukewarm in the glass, and
then drinking it like that

00:33:41.549 --> 00:33:43.090
because that's never
how you're going

00:33:43.090 --> 00:33:44.350
to drink your vodka, right?

00:33:44.350 --> 00:33:47.002
So you want to
basically road test it.

00:33:47.002 --> 00:33:48.460
And that's one of
the things that I

00:33:48.460 --> 00:33:54.100
share in the book is that
there wasn't one gin or whisky

00:33:54.100 --> 00:33:56.540
or vodka or even
tequila, et cetera,

00:33:56.540 --> 00:33:58.660
that I was always
entirely satisfied.

00:33:58.660 --> 00:34:01.540
You would reach for
one gin for a Negroni.

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:05.150
And then you'd reach for another
one for, say, an Aviation.

00:34:05.150 --> 00:34:07.500
What I started doing
is creating blends.

00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:09.900
So as I have all of these
different opportunities

00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:11.760
in-- because that's
what I call the bottles.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:13.260
I call them
opportunities behind me.

00:34:13.260 --> 00:34:15.440
I said, OK, I'm going
to bring them together.

00:34:15.440 --> 00:34:17.280
So then I would create
these master blends

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:18.240
that I would keep
in the speed well

00:34:18.240 --> 00:34:20.940
at the bar that would have four
different types of gin in it.

00:34:20.940 --> 00:34:24.320
And then I would have this
master cocktail spirit

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:26.929
based upon these blends
and my years of experience

00:34:26.929 --> 00:34:27.739
of blending.

00:34:27.739 --> 00:34:32.300
And then, aha, every gin drink
that I ever made was awesome.

00:34:32.300 --> 00:34:36.449
So if you want to do that,
like, if you're a gin nerd,

00:34:36.449 --> 00:34:38.870
then buy the four
bottle that I prescribe.

00:34:38.870 --> 00:34:42.500
And make the blends, and see
if all of your gin cocktails

00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:44.900
turn out perfect.

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:46.400
AUDIENCE: How would
you characterize

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:49.170
the art of bartending
in this country today?

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:52.699
DUGGAN MCDONNELL: Wow, the
art of bartending today.

00:34:52.699 --> 00:34:58.810
I'm going to actually say that
the art has started to slip.

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:00.405
And it's actually
going into a realm

00:35:00.405 --> 00:35:02.220
where it's just
craft and discipline.

00:35:02.220 --> 00:35:04.560
And I think that that's OK.

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:06.830
I think that we got
overwhelmed with art.

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:10.670
And now there's so many
options-- so many bottles,

00:35:10.670 --> 00:35:12.420
as I've been talking
about, so many things

00:35:12.420 --> 00:35:17.100
that my concern, Mike, in how
I'm answering this question

00:35:17.100 --> 00:35:20.370
is that I hope that
mixologists are not

00:35:20.370 --> 00:35:23.300
staring into their
navels, more concerned

00:35:23.300 --> 00:35:25.480
by the three different
types of bitters that

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:27.570
are going into the
cocktails and the hand

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:29.440
carving of an ice
for an old fashioned

00:35:29.440 --> 00:35:32.520
or where their local
Meyer lemons are

00:35:32.520 --> 00:35:37.230
sourced because that's
really not what it's about.

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:39.590
I think that cocktails
should be artfully made.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:44.960
But ultimately, I still
hope that people go to bars

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:47.780
to get laid and to
have a great time

00:35:47.780 --> 00:35:51.468
and to forget and to
cope with gentrification

00:35:51.468 --> 00:35:55.760
and to wake up with a hangover
in the morning and be proud.

00:35:55.760 --> 00:35:59.510
And I hope that this
cocktail Renaissance does not

00:35:59.510 --> 00:36:02.740
screw all that up for us because
cocktails should, frankly,

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:04.570
still equal a great time.

00:36:04.570 --> 00:36:06.660
And so in spite of
all my pontificating

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:12.110
and my seriousness about
where our palates come

00:36:12.110 --> 00:36:14.340
from in this community in
this part of the world,

00:36:14.340 --> 00:36:16.290
I still believe that,
frankly, a cocktail

00:36:16.290 --> 00:36:18.240
needs to be a great time.

00:36:18.240 --> 00:36:20.790
And hopefully, it'll
be a balanced one.

00:36:20.790 --> 00:36:21.870
Thank you.

00:36:21.870 --> 00:36:24.125
[APPLAUSE]

